nt community had been pushed onto the path of change by the end of the nineteenth century, how much the “peasantry” itself had become increasingly heterogeneous in outlook and occupation, and the rapidity with which these processes had begun to corrode the legitimacy of the older order. Miller concludes that unrest was concentrated mostly among peasant communities for whom the benefits the vital interactions between social unequals that had maintained a fragile social peace in the countryside had been radically eroded; he furthermore identifies the prominent role played by that spectrum of persons that retained their ties to their villages, but stood toward the margins of rural life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aGovernment, Resistance tozRussia (Federation)zKurskai︠a︡ oblastʹxHistoryy20th century. 0aPeasantszRussia (Federation)zKurskai︠a︡ oblastʹxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial changezRussia (Federation)zKurskai︠a︡ oblastʹxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial conflictzRussia (Federation)zKurskai︠a︡ oblastʹxHistoryy20th century. 0aVillageszRussia (Federation)zKurskai︠a︡ oblastʹxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aAgriculture, Peasants, Revolutions, Rural conditions, Russia, Social change, Social conflict.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155225505423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155225505/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  